[ ] add idempotent cleanup commands for what doctor finds $ doctor reports and never fixes, so the findings need owners. the first run surfaced the initial set: four orphaned sidecars left behind by charter archiving, five stale entries in the platform .next.json, and abandoned tmp staging files. each cleanup is an explicit idempotent command per file surface; a future doctor fix flag is sugar that invokes these commands, never fixing logic of its own $ !2 +cli #019f2ec3-df61-7e1d-8c93-e558c61dc5b3
    >[ ] make charter archiving remove the charter sidecar $ archive charter moves the actions file but leaves the hidden json behind — the source of all four orphans found 2026-07-04. fixing the producer beats sweeping forever $ +cli,bug #019f2ec3-df62-7b54-812e-38660fb5a280
    >[ ] add a sidecar prune command $ drop entries whose uuid matches no action in the file or its completed archive, delete whole sidecars with no actions file, and sweep orphaned tmp staging files. reads what doctor reads, fixes what doctor flags, idempotent by construction $ +cli #019f2ec3-df63-7d2b-ac86-088a5c16323d
[ ] stop deriving created timestamps from action identity $ created_from_uuid reads the creation time from a uuid's top 48 bits, but that only holds for v7 — a v4 or otherwise hand-authored id makes those bits random, and 12 actions in this very workspace carry created dates between the years 5081 and 10143. they reach the RDF graph, so any recency query in the query system surfaces fiction first. the unwrap_or_else(now) guard is dead code: 48 random bits always land inside chrono's range, so from_timestamp never returns None. root cause is deriving time from identity — any id we did not mint corrupts the clock. decided 2026-07-10: keep v7 as the default and use its embedded time when genuinely present, but eat v4 gracefully by stamping the date we first see the action rather than interrogating its bits. found by doctor review, but doctor itself was blind to it — the caught-nothing case the trust charter exists to close $ !1 +library,bug #019f4d0b-7293-73ff-8da9-2c8b9ad82251
    >[ ] make created_from_uuid eat non-v7 ids $ version-check before reading the timestamp bits: get_version_num() == 7 or return None, so the existing now() fallback finally fires instead of manufacturing a far-future date. this is the whole graceful-v4 fix — one guard turns the dead branch live $ +library,bug #019f4d0b-7295-7152-af2a-13941a913945
    >[ ] add a doctor check for created timestamps outside a sane window $ the invariant "created is a real past date" is written down nowhere that runs — the schema types it as a string (year 8723 is a valid string), lint W005 checks the future but runs pre-hydration on the DSL while the garbage lives in the sidecar, so neither fires. a doctor finding over hydrated created (before workspace genesis or after now) is the check that would have caught all 12, and belongs with the other cross-file sidecar invariants $ +library #019f4d0b-7297-7948-a2a6-00a18dce02ff
    >[ ] restamp the already-corrupted created entries $ the 12 far-future timestamps are live in committed sidecars and cannot self-heal — the guard fix only changes future stamping. one-shot correction: replace each with the honest date-we-see-it now that the derivation is fixed, so the graph stops returning fiction $ +cli #019f4d0b-7299-7d95-81c9-d976f6efe416
    >[ ] make the sidecar acts map serialize deterministically $ CharterMetadata.acts is a HashMap written with to_string_pretty into a committed file, so every save reshuffles key order and produces a diff of pure noise — the working tree already carries a 13-insert/13-delete caldav sidecar churn with zero semantic change. BTreeMap keys the file by uuid string and the noise is gone for good; also makes the file a stable audit surface, which is the whole sidecar-trust point $ +library #019f4d0b-729b-71d8-967b-1f9ea1a3028d
[ ] make charter/sidecar association survive file moves $ the sidecar binds to its charter by path convention (.stem.json beside stem.actions), so a moved or renamed .actions file orphans its sidecar and silently drops the metadata — most dangerously the irreplaceable CalDAV merge bases (source_vevent, scheduled_at_sync, due_date_sync) that cannot be recomputed. the honest posture is not "keep them together" (unenforceable against a hand mv) but "make separation recoverable and loud": re-join by id, heal in the loader, let doctor flag the mess $ !2 +library #019f4f42-a83a-7df6-9937-7fb79d9934ba
    >[x] hydrate acts from a workspace-wide uuid union $ DONE 2026-07-10: read_workspace now folds every sidecar under the charter root into one uuid->ActMeta map (collect_sidecar_acts) and hydrates each action against it, so a sidecar orphaned by a move still reaches its actions by uuid. identical in the normal case — an action's uuid lives only in its own sidecar — and self-healing on move. merge_act keeps the sync bases regardless of file order so an empty re-stamp never clobbers a real record. the conventional path is still read only to report a corrupt sidecar $ +library %2026-07-10T00:00#019f4f42-a83d-70fc-a831-8c811fc46100
    >[ ] add the optional charter-id header to .actions files $ the durable-resilience layer on top of the uuid heal: an OPTIONAL leading #<uuid> declaring the charter, rendered away by the editor (conceal to the charter title, like #uuid to an icon) so the human never types or sees it. it lets the .actions file announce its own charter even when empty and decouples it from every filename, so doctor can triangulate identity if any of the three files is renamed or lost. it is a REFERENCE not a second declaration — frontmatter, or the header itself when there is no .md, stays authoritative and doctor verifies agreement. touches the three-artifact round-trip so it is real work: tree-sitter-actions grammar.js gets a charter_id node distinguishable from an action by the absent brackets and regenerates the parser; core parse_document surfaces charter_id; the formatter emits it with a round-trip test per Decision 33; a Topiary query formats the line; the LSP conceals the id and projects the title; doctor cross-checks header against frontmatter against sidecar charter.id. sequenced AFTER the heal, never gating it $ +library,cli,nvim #019f4f42-a83d-7a46-a419-c65a0da25d1a
    >[x] record charter.id in the sidecar at charter creation $ DONE 2026-07-10: core stamp_charter_id (idempotent, freeze-preserving) records charter.id in the sidecar; add_charter calls it best-effort after creating the .actions file. note: add_charter charters already carry a frontmatter id, so this mainly makes their sidecar self-identifying for the re-join heal — the charters that need the recorded id for identity are the implicit ones, which the backfill owns $ +cli,library %2026-07-10T00:00#019f4f85-2677-7ab7-ad6c-d72d7577d1e3
    >[x] resolve charter identity from the sidecar, a derived id yields to it $ DONE 2026-07-10: loader resolution pass overrides a non-explicit v5-seed id with the sidecar charter.id; frontmatter_has_id_key guards a declared id from being superseded; inert until ids are written; tested both ways. new precedence: explicit frontmatter id wins, else a recorded sidecar charter.id, else the v5 seed $ !1 +library %2026-07-10T00:00#019f4f85-2677-787f-bf66-8591849b6d38
    >[ ] doctor flags a sidecar charter.id that disagrees with its charter $ once identity is recorded the one dangerous state is a sidecar charter.id that contradicts the charter's declared id — a hand-edited frontmatter or a mis-joined sidecar. a finding over that conflict, frontmatter authoritative, closes the loop; the transient no-id-yet state is a backfill target not a warning $ +library #019f4f85-2677-7223-99a2-4cd969733a54
    >[ ] backfill charter.id for existing charters $ the read side is inert until ids exist and every current charter runs on a derived id. a cleanup command stamps charter.id = the charter's current resolved id for any charter lacking one, freezing today's identities so they survive future renames. same freeze-not-remint discipline as restamping created; belongs with the idempotent cleanup lane $ +cli #019f4f85-2677-7978-ac19-0d925fa741e1
